<!-- ABOUT -->
<section class="about" id="about">
  <div class="about-grid">
    <div class="about-text">
      <div class="section-label">Heritage & History</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">A Window Into <span>Ancient India</span></h2>
      <div class="divider left"></div>
      <p>The Ajanta Caves are 30 rock-cut Buddhist cave monuments dating from the 2nd century BCE to approximately 480 CE, located in the Aurangabad district of Maharashtra, India. Carved into the sheer face of a horseshoe-shaped basalt gorge above the Waghora River, these caves served as monsoon retreats and places of worship for Buddhist monks.</p>
      <div class="highlight-box">"The finest surviving examples of ancient Indian art — particularly painting — which is of the greatest archaeological, religious and artistic significance." — UNESCO</div>
      <p>Rediscovered in 1819 by British officer John Smith during a tiger hunt, the caves had been hidden in jungle for nearly a millennium. They contain some of the best-preserved examples of ancient fresco painting and intricate stone sculpture in the world, depicting the life of the Buddha and various Jataka tales.</p>
      <p>The site encompasses two distinct phases of construction — the Hinayana (Theravada) phase and the later Mahayana phase — representing a profound evolution in Buddhist thought and artistic expression over six centuries.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="about-img-wrap">
      <img src="https://th.bing.com/th/id/OIP._a1pkuNI8KJLZyV9wz1cyQHaLG?w=186&h=279&c=7&r=0&o=7&dpr=1.3&pid=1.7&rm=3" alt="Padmapani painting in Cave 1, Ajanta" loading="lazy" />
      <div class="about-img-caption">Bodhisattva Padmapani — Cave 1 · One of India's most iconic paintings</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

